<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,151,498]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,326,311,337]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body is oval, relatively small and very convex. Majority of studied specimens have contrasting orange spots on black elytra. Dorsal metatibial spurs of males are modified – curved and hooked apically. The species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi, 2010" authorityName="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2010" box="[450,608,392,417]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ceylonicus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[450,608,392,417]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">E. ceylonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[618,712,392,418]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but the dorsal pattern is orange and present only in anterior portion of elytra. Genitalia similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2010" box="[600,753,432,457]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picturatus">
<emphasis box="[600,753,432,457]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">E. picturatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differ in details of sternite 9, parameres and slightly wider prehensor. Well distinguishable also on the basis of morphology of dorsal metatibial spur of males.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
