<subSubSection lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1335,2001]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,350,1335,1361]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[362,474,1335,1361]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Holotype</typeStatus>
, male. Body hemispherical, TL/EW 1.1, convex, covered with yellow suberect setae. Head black with slightly lighter anterior margin of clypeus, pronotum black, elytra with pattern consisting of adscutellar and humeral orange spots. Posterior portion of elytra black. Legs light brown. Mouthparts brownish, proximal antennomeres yellowish, darkening distally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1335,2001]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Head with distinct punctation, punctures separated by ca. 1.0 diameter. Eyes big, protuberant; head 1.8 X wider than interocular space. Antennae filiform, reaching basal 1/3 of elytra. Antennomere 1 cylindrical, curved, antennomere 2 short, globular, antennomere 3 distinctly longer than antennomere 2, narrow, antennomere 4–10 1.5 X longer than antennomere 3, apical antennomere ca. 1.5 X longer than preapical one. Palpomeres of maxillary palpi moderately wide.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1335,2001]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Pronotum small, slightly convex, covered with distinct punctation, punctures separated by 1.0–1.5 diameters, anterolateral corners almost rectangular, somewhat obtuse, projecting anteriorly; lateral margins straight; posterolateral corners acute; base of pronotum subtrapezoidal, with complete margination along basal margin; PW/PL 2.9. Scutellum relatively big, punctured as on pronotum, equilaterally triangular. Angle between pronotum and elytra not marked in dorsal outline.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,1335,2001]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Elytra oval, with distinctly explanate lateral margins, widest in the middle, punctation stronger than on pronotum, punctures separated by 1.0–1.5 diameters; humeri well marked; EL/EW 1.0; EL/PL 4.8; EW/PW 1.7.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,778]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Legs moderately long. Hind tibial spurs well developed, dorsal one elongated and modified – straight, apical half slightly widened and hooked at apex, 0.8 X as long as tarsomere 1 and only slightly longer than ventral spur. Ventral spur distinctly curved.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,778]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Longitudinal ridge on ventrite 1 present in basal portion. Apex of ventrite 5 with wide and deep emargination. Apex of tergite 7 unmodified.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,778]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Sternite 9 (L 0.63, 
<geoCoordinate box="[425,515,352,378]" degrees="0.28" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" precision="555" value="-0.28">W 0.28</geoCoordinate>
) subtriangular, apodemes fused basally, apex deeply emarginated, with a few apical setae and small projection pointing inwardly. Tergite 8 (L 1.10, 
<geoCoordinate box="[980,1068,392,418]" degrees="0.57" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" precision="555" value="-0.57">W 0.57</geoCoordinate>
) moderately sclerotized, apical portion small, deeply and narrowly emarginated, with arcuate apex, bearing row of short setae on apical margin, with a pair of very long apodemes diverging basally; tergite 9 (L 0.80, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1054,1144,472,498]" degrees="0.60" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" precision="555" value="-0.6">W 0.60</geoCoordinate>
) moderately sclerotized, apical portion small, with minute setae at apex, with a pair of long apodemes strongly diverging basally. Tegmen (L 0.65, 
<geoCoordinate box="[309,397,552,578]" degrees="0.60" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" precision="555" value="-0.6">W 0.60</geoCoordinate>
) well sclerotized, parameres straight, widening apically, apices with 2 small denticles on inner margin, mesal process very narrow and short, much shorter than parameres. Penis (L 0.47, 
<geoCoordinate box="[1336,1428,592,618]" degrees="0.09" direction="west" orientation="longitude" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" precision="555" value="-0.09">W 0.09</geoCoordinate>
) small, moderately sclerotized, pala very narrow and elongate, parameroids as long as pala, apical process slightly shorter than pala.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,152,778]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,296,711,737]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Female.</emphasis>
Dorsal pattern less contrasting than in males, no uniformly colored specimens of females are known. Prehensor tubular, straight, moderately long, relatively narrow.
</paragraph>
<caption box="[151,1093,1694,1718]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" startId="30.[151,255,1694,1718]" targetBox="[151,1436,828,1670]" targetPageId="30">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1093,1694,1718]" box="[151,1093,1694,1718]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,294,1694,1718]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">FIGURE 23.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi, 2010" authorityName="Ruta &amp; Yoshitomi" authorityYear="2010" box="[301,592,1695,1718]" class="Insecta" family="Scirtidae" genus="Exochomoscirtes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="takizawai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[301,592,1695,1718]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Exochomoscirtes takizawai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[599,684,1694,1717]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, female, prehensor and bursal sclerite.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1766,2033]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,338,1766,1792]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Variability.</emphasis>
TL/EW males: 1.1–1.2 (1.1), TL/EW females: 1.2. Dorsal pattern very variable – elytra from uniformly black to black with distinct pattern consisting of spots situated in basal portion of elytra (one adscutellar and one humeral macula on each elytron), in some specimens indistinct lighter area is present in adsutural portion of posterior half of elytra.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1436,1766,2033]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,389,1926,1952]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Measurements.</emphasis>
Males (n = 6): TL 2.80–3.55 (3.21), PL 0.50–0.65 (0.59), PW 1.55–2.00 (1.77), EL 2.55– 3.15 (2.88), EW 2.40–3.10 (2.82). Females (n = 6): TL 2.95–3.30 (3.12), PL 0.50–0.60 (0.57), PW 1.58–1.75 (1.69), EL 2.60–2.95 (2.78), EW 2.45–2.70 (2.57).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,151,298]" box="[198,460,151,178]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,359,151,177]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Distribution.</emphasis>
Borneo.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,151,298]" box="[198,771,191,218]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,290,191,217]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Bology.</emphasis>
Larvae develop in phytotelmata (
<figureCitation box="[685,757,192,218]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="14.[151,255,1775,1799]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,197,1749]" captionTargetId="figure-46@14.[151,1436,197,1749]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURE 9. Exochomoscirtes takizawai sp. nov., habitat. A) Mahua waterfall, Sabah, Borneo; B) phytotelmata in buttress root inhabited by larvae; C) adult female on the root (H. Yoshitomi phot.)." pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="31" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="31.[151,1436,151,298]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,338,231,257]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named after Dr. Haruo Takizawa, who is an excellent taxonomist of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[151,328,272,298]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Chrysomelidae</taxonomicName>
and collector of the 
<typeStatus box="[570,676,272,298]" pageId="31" pageNumber="32">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
